# Skipping GitHub Actions Workflows

There are several ways to prevent a GitHub Actions workflow from running.

## Option 1 - Cancel a Running Workflow (GitHub UI)

If a workflow has already started:

1. Go to the **Actions** tab of your repository.
2. Select the running workflow.
3. Click **Cancel workflow** in the upper-right corner.

This immediately stops the workflow execution.

---

## Option 2 - Skip Workflows Using the Commit Message

GitHub automatically skips workflows triggered by `push` or `pull_request` when the commit message contains one of the following keywords:

- `[skip ci]`
- `[ci skip]`
- `[no ci]`
- `[skip actions]`
- `[actions skip]`

### Example

```bash
git commit -m "Update documentation [skip ci]"
git push
```

or

```bash
git commit -m "Fix typo [ci skip]"
git push
```

The workflow will not be triggered for that commit.

> **Note:** These keywords only affect workflows triggered by `push` and `pull_request` events. They do **not** skip workflows started by events such as `workflow_dispatch`, `schedule`, `repository_dispatch`, or other event types.

---

## Option 3 - Skip Using the `skip-checks` Trailer

GitHub also supports the following commit trailer:

```text
skip-checks:true
```

Example:

```text
Improve README

skip-checks:true
```

This has the same effect as the skip keywords for supported events.

---

## Summary

| Method | When to Use |
|---------|-------------|
| Cancel workflow (UI) | Stop a workflow that is already running |
| `[skip ci]` or similar | Prevent a workflow from starting on a push or pull request |
| `skip-checks:true` | Alternative commit trailer to skip supported workflows |